\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.9}{\ignorespaces Example of successive ascent flight path, where each segment has a north length of $400$ meters. Each segment has a path angle $\gamma $ of $0^{\circ }$, $10^{\circ }$, $20^{\circ }$, and $30^{\circ }$ respectively.}}{25}{figure.caption.17}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.10}{\ignorespaces Position and Velocity error over the ascent course. Notice that each large jump in error corresponds to the corner of a new ascending course.}}{26}{figure.caption.18}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.11}{\ignorespaces Control inputs for the successive ascent course. Notice that when the aircraft is at too steep of an angle to maintain lift and stability by forward propulsion and elevator control alone, it also uses the vertical rotors to keep it on trajectory.}}{26}{figure.caption.19}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.12}{\ignorespaces Pitch, flight path angle, reference flight path angle, and angle of attack for the aircraft over the course.}}{27}{figure.caption.20}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.13}{\ignorespaces Position and Velocity Error Plots. Notice that the initial vertical position error causes a massive error oscillation pattern in the north position and north velocity errors.}}{29}{figure.caption.21}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.14}{\ignorespaces Deltas for initial step error. Notice the large spikes in the forward thruster, and periods of zero. This is caused by the position and velocity error oscillations.}}{29}{figure.caption.22}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.15}{\ignorespaces Pitch, flight path angle, flight path angle reference, and angle of attack for step error trajectory tracking.}}{30}{figure.caption.23}%
