\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.1}{\ignorespaces Three examples of obstacle fields are presented. The 2x2 and 3x3 grids run fairly well. The algorithm breaks down on the 4x4 grid; it does not find a good initialization point.}}{58}{figure.caption.37}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.2}{\ignorespaces Point to point RRT expansion process. Two configurations are shown. A random point $Rand$ is selected in the configuration space, and line is drawn between $Rand$ and the nearest existing node $N_i$. A new candidate node $N_k$ is placed a distance $d$ from $N_i$. If the line from $N_i$ to $N_k$ is not obstructed, it is added. Otherwise, it is discarded, as in the Invalid Case.}}{59}{figure.caption.38}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.3}{\ignorespaces Straight line RRT example on 4x3 grid of obstacles}}{59}{figure.caption.39}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.4}{\ignorespaces RRT algorithm integrating Dubins path into planning. From \blx@tocontentsinit {0}\citeauthor {uav_book} \blx@tocontentsinit {0}\cite {uav_book} Fig. 12.12, pg. 255}}{60}{figure.caption.40}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.5}{\ignorespaces An example of a Non-Convex and a Convex shape. A line segment can be drawn between points within the Non-Convex shape and leave the shape temporarily. This is because of the reflex vertex, which has an internal angle greater than $\pi $ radians. Such is not the case with the convex shape, which maintains all internal points.}}{61}{figure.caption.41}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.6}{\ignorespaces Showing geometrical intuition for half-plane switching. $\hat {n}$ represents the vector normal to the half-plane bisecting line, $\vec {r}$ represents an arbitrary point the bisecting line passes through, and $\vec {p_i}$ represents a given point in the plane. This shows three different scenarios: the projections of $\vec {r}$, $\vec {p_1}$, and $\vec {p_2}$ onto $\hat {n}$. $\hat {n}^\top p_1$, is less than $\hat {n}^\top r$ and $(\hat {n}^\top p_1) \hat {n}$ is on the opposite side of the plane as $\hat {n}$, while the opposite is true for $\vec {p_2}$.}}{62}{figure.caption.42}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.7}{\ignorespaces Geometry of Rectangular flight corridor, with four normal vectors and vertex points respectively. }}{62}{figure.caption.43}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.8}{\ignorespaces Non-Convex Union of two Safe Flight Corridors}}{63}{figure.caption.44}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.9}{\ignorespaces Aircraft flying section of Dubins Path with straight lines, and connected with arcs of minimum turning radius. Anything with sharper curvature, and the aircraft will be unable to perform the turn.}}{64}{figure.caption.45}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.10}{\ignorespaces Turn rate constraint for Safe Flight Corridor intersection. Demonstrates the maximum turning angle between two SFCS using a superimposed circular flight path of the minimum allowable turning radius. If $\chi $ was any greater, the minimum turning radius would not be able to fit inside of the two safe flight corridors, and the aircraft's minimum turning radius would be violated.}}{64}{figure.caption.46}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.11}{\ignorespaces Arc section of two concentric circles, called an annulus. The line from $P_1$ to $P_2$ demonstrates this is a non-convex region.}}{65}{figure.caption.47}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.12}{\ignorespaces Diagram of sampled annulus constraints}}{66}{figure.caption.48}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.13}{\ignorespaces Diagram of initial RRT output and all possible alternative connections between nodes. Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest possible route in the end.}}{66}{figure.caption.49}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.14}{\ignorespaces Diagram of relationships between Control Points. This example shows that the vectors between control points are the control points of the derivative.}}{68}{figure.caption.50}%
